segments.text: But Sunday, last Sunday, and get stuff from all... See, we have a veterinarian that's a good ophthalmologist.
He's an ophthalmologist specialist.
So we have quite a few... Last July.
We have a good overall picture of specialization.
We have a radiologist.
We have some people I get literature from.
Radiologists.
You know, one of the big problems is that
and I don't know the answer to it totally, is that veterinarians have had to, maybe by necessity, but also probably because of their own conservative nature and design, be their own PR.
And so it's just like I've been on the public relation committees of the local association and the state association.

for on and off for the last 25 years and they get together and they have lots of good ideas but they don't really know you know it's like a lawyer trying to defend himself they really don't know what they're doing you know if really a lot of stuff could be gotten in the media both electronic media and print media if but you've got to you can't just go down and say look we'd like to have something on about veterinary medicine or send them a letter we'd like to have something on about veterinary medicine
You've got to go down there and make a presentation.
Here's what we can give you.
Here are the subjects.
Here's the guy that's going to present it.
Tom, you know what Bernie and I used to say?
Excuse me, Bernie.
We told each other this a dozen times, one of my large animal exporters.
We'd say, you idiot, you're too busy working to be a good businessman.
Well, that's true.
And that's it.
Yeah.
You really are.
That's exactly right.
James Herriot's done more for veterinary public relations and all the organized veterinary societies since the eons of time.
That's right.
He really has.
But you know, your experience on that TV station is really a good indicator because people love animals and they like people who like animals.
And all you need to do is make people know you're out there.
Quite frankly, if I wanted to, I could be on television
at least once a month or twice a month.
Because I've got probably 150 two-minute television vignettes that I've written and done.
And I have subject material and all that.
I tried to get the state association several years ago.

I told them that if they would hire somebody to take all my television tapes and radio tapes and to put them together and edit them and then with a list of subject material, then they could send that out to
local veterinary associations and say, here's a how-to kit to approach your media.

You can look at these, see how your formats are, have a whole bunch of subject material, and if they went to their local television or radio station and said, look, we'd like to get this on, here's a whole bunch of subjects that our people can talk about.
And it would come under the Animal Public Service.
Jim Humphreys did this.
Mm-hmm.
Yeah, and he was very successful in Dallas.
Well, we're approaching it, but like I say, we have a long ways to go.
We need to hang.
Every time we get an opportunity,
Like I was talking about, to get our foot in the door or to do this, it helps to spend their money.
But veterinarians get together and they get all pumped up and say, oh, we can do this.
And it's like Philip Martin with the little article in the paper.
He loses his mind trying to get people, veterinarians, to contribute.
It's in there every day.
And finally, I suggest that he came and got all my radio tapes because people call and ask questions.
I said, this will certainly give you all the questions you ever want to write about.
I'm trying to write a book.
Are you?

But to get veterinarians to do this, you know, to get veterinarians to do this, I mean, you get somebody pumped up, somebody writes one or two, and then they forget about it, and they go on, and then the whole movement just kind of sags and dies, you know.
I have some experiences, I think.
I lived in Mexico for years.
I've done zoo work, exotic work, ranch work.
I have 50 articles, pictures, notes of true animal adventure experiences.
Some of them are real comical.
I write very factual articles.
I have some with me.
I have a lot of them that hold pictures.
I've written UTSA Press, A&M Press, sent them two or three articles that I've finished that are true adventure.
But I write factual, you know.
Yeah.
Joe Blow or Capstick could write them up and make them tremendously interesting.
Yeah.
I hope you'll pass a few of those along.
Well, I tell you, I was wondering, I was just thinking, I said, I don't know if this gentleman is interested in, you know, but... No, I want some good stories, good videos.
Well, I have some stuff.
I know it's interesting because I get in a party some days and get talking to somebody, and we talk for an hour.
But I have written and rewritten and rewritten, and I have two or three finished.
I thought a writer just wrote it one time, and that was it.
That's it.
I think all of us, if we've read Harriet's books, and I know I did when I was reading his books.
I found myself, and I started off as a large animal, interested in large animals in a small Indiana town.
You know, I was out one time when I was, in fact, I was a senior student that's been there and left town, and I kind of looked after his practice while he was gone.

He was going to be gone two weeks, and I had a call, and, you know, first calf, heifer calving, and out in the crop shed in the middle of the night, and the old farmer told me, he said, well, I think you can do it, you know, and I,
I was there struggling trying to get that calf turned around.
I just finished reading that.
Yeah, yeah, and he was standing there saying, well, Dr. Turner do this, well, Dr. Turner, I mean, it was exactly like that.
He had that calf on there.
I just finished reading that story.
Yeah, yeah, yeah.
My wife has every one of the English veterinarians, and I have a book signed by one of my clients, and I've read most of them.
And I said, man, I've been that route.
Yeah, we've all been there.
We've all been there.
If we've done a mixed practice or done any, they have experiences in small animals.
Oh, yeah.
But the thing about it, we're all too busy working to put it down.
And a lot of us can't write.
And writing like that is a true talent.
And I can't lie, I'm too factual.
He's done such a wonderful job of it.
He really has.
You know, if everybody said, well, you know, I bet if you'd have written down all the things that happened, you could have written a book like that.
And I said, well, I could have written down all those things, but I probably could not have written a book like that.
Couldn't have written a book like that.
Well, I got started in Mexico when I was down there and had a lot of time.
And I was out running around in a Jeep or an airplane or riding hard back in the mountains.
And so I took a lot of pictures when I was on foot in the mountains.
And that's what really got me to thinking in 1948 through 51 when I was down there.
And I still have stuff from then on.
Plus, every day now, I go on a night call and it's really an experience.
I said, you know, that'd make good article, if I could write it up for you.
So that's why I have so many that are, you know.
We sent out that little flyer in the newsletter asking people to send in this kind of thing.
I don't know if we'll get much response.
You know, speaking of that, you talk about things like that.
One of the funniest things that ever happened to me was back when I started doing the zoo work and Fred Olin,
I'm sorry, where I am.
Fred was there, and he came down here from Illinois, and he went to work for me.
And I was at Southwest Research and doing the zoo work, and only spent a very limited time in my practice and everything.
And so he would cover for me.
And he, Fred, subsequently went back to medical school, and he's an orthopedic surgeon, a human orthopedic surgeon.
But I was at a party one night.
And it was about, I think, probably 12, between 12 and 1 o'clock in the morning.
And it was a formal party, you know, the tux and everything.
And I got this call from the answering service.
And the county answering service was laughing.
And she said, well, Dr. Weiss, she said, I've got a call.
And the guy's at a phone booth.
And he says he has a constipated elephant.
And she said, I questioned him.
And he said, it's real.
He wasn't pulling a joke or anything else.
And so I said, good grief.
I said, good grief.
And so I took the number.
And I thought, Jesus, I don't want to have to leave this party.
And so I called Fred and woke him up.
And I said, Fred, I've got this call.
And I said, it's kind of a specialized call.
And I could only think of one veterinarian in the whole world who's qualified to take it.
And that's you.
And he said, oh, come on.
What is it?
What is it?
And I said, well, just call this number.
I can't tell you what it's about.
But just call this number.
And I said, the guy's waiting at a phone booth and everything.
And it is an emergency.
And so the phone went on back to the party.
We got home about 2 or 2.30.
4.30 in the morning, my phone rang.
And I picked it up, and he said, biggest goddamn elephant I ever saw.
And it was a little circus, was wintering out here in the south side of town, and it was this big, this old elephant, and he was down, and Fred gave him an enema with a garden hose.
and gave him a great big shot of one of those injectable laxatives.
I can't even think of the name of it.
Yeah.
Stiglin.
That is a story.
That was a funny one.
Oh, bubba hubba.
What is it, a regal?
Well, I use it.
I grow it down, and you use Stiglin.
It's a little stronger.
And you use Copan, which is mild.
Yeah, but back then, it was probably...
I don't even remember what it was.
There haven't been many adventures with a constipated elephant.
No, that was it.
We still laugh about that.
Fred probably never treated that one before, Eddie.
Well, what do you think?
Good to see you.
Well, I want to get with you.
Yes, sir.
You know, when you're convenient.
Because I've got, this is since 1948.
And I have stuff that I went up to Kerrville to an ostrich farm the other day.
And a lot of these things just...
Like we say, we all have them.
You get in some crazy things in exotics.
One thing, at least you're saving it in your conscience.
The main thing is, especially, you know, I think you get more out in a different environment at farms and ranches and dairies than you do in your clinic.
Because in a clinic, you're in the same place.
So that's why I think they're more interesting if you're in different environments and different farms and different, everything, environment and everything.
But anyway, we all have them.
Everybody that's in practice has them.
I think so.
It's just a matter of writing them up properly.
So are the people you've ever contacted.
Oh, the people.
Doc Anderson.
You've been here for Doc Anderson?
Yes.
I've got an article on her.
I started years ago.
Is she still alive?
I don't know, she's too mean to lie.
We could have let you talk a little bit.
No, no, I'm not here to talk.
Listen, absolutely.
What I would like to do, but I didn't want to stop the conversation because that's the kind of stuff I was really after is what you were talking about.

But let's, if you will, go back and let me ask each of you to sort of identify yourself, explain a little bit about your background, how you got into veterinary medicine, a little biographical sketch, if you will.

And then I'd like to sort of focus on your area of expertise, and if you will, each of you kind of add to it, because this is what makes this kind of an interview work, is that people interrelate and ask questions of each other.
So don't feel like you're just listening to me and whoever's talking.
But Tom, you now are focusing primarily

birds right here well i'll do general small animal work yeah and uh i want to follow that up and then uh elder or an elder an elder i'd like to talk to you about how you got into medical medicine and then you were one of the early women licensed practitioners in texas i believe i'd like to follow up on that and then all of us talk a little bit about women in the practice but that's clearly one of the changing profiles first one around here
I took the State Board with her at 48.
Now there's a class at A&M, I assume you know, the last two years, over half girls.
Oh, it's been longer than that.
It's been longer than that, because Archie Flowers, the year that Barbara Lewis was up there, was over 50.
You're looking at a steep change in the whole profile of the profession.
Yeah, the most dramatic of which I can identify with when we go to seminars,
Because there used to not be a line at all in the ladies' room.
It's the truth.
But you know, when I first started teaching at A&M in 1969, I still remember my first class.
I'd come over from South Louisiana.
And I had 130 men in that class, one woman,
And I swear I believe 30 or 40 of those men were asleep.
They were all in uniform.
It was 8 o'clock class.
And I'm like, gosh, what have I gotten into?
And I didn't know what the problem was.
I hadn't even started lecturing yet.
So I knew my lecture wasn't that bad.
And they were asleep.
Well, they'd been out, you know, doing their thing.
Well, now it's the Texas Hall of Fame.
Yeah.
That's right.
They're doing that.
And then, Mason, you're...
Well, I've done strictly large animal work.
That's all I ever did.
Okay, let's talk about that.
But you're doing more zoo type?
That's what I really like, and that's what I'm doing most of the time is exotic zoo ranch type animals.
So let's talk about that.
So each of you represented in a way a special niche in the whole
I'm sure we're all very opinionated.
That's good, too.
You know I am.
Well, I know she is.
She knows I am.
Tom does.
We all are.
So who wants to kick off with a sort of a personal sketch now?
Chris, I'm Dr. Tom Weiss, and I started, I graduated in 1957 from Michigan State University.
I grew up in a small
rural town in Indiana, Wabash, Indiana, and was interested primarily when I was in veterinary school in doing large animal or farm practice.
Why did you get into vet practice?
Well, I worked for a cousin on his farm during the summertime, and then a close personal friend of my parents was a veterinarian, and so I started working for him some part-time on weekends as a kid.

and all of a sudden decided, you know, gosh, this is what I want to be, a veterinarian, and went on to veterinary school, and fortunately picked something that I was loved and was well adapted to and did well at.
And so when I graduated, I practiced in a small animal practice in Fort Wayne, Indiana, for several months, and then went in the Air Force, applied for a commission in the Air Force.
It was either that or get drafted back then.
And so I got commissioned in the Air Force and was stationed here in San Antonio at Kelly Air Force Base.
Everybody used to ask me, you know, what in the world is a veterinarian doing in the Air Force?
You know, I said, well, he castrates jets.
But I fell in love with San Antonio at that time and also with a Texas gal and wanted to really stay here.
And when I got out of the Air Force, why?
Some of the local veterinarians, I used to have the advantage of inspecting about 50 food establishments in San Antonio once a month that supplied food to the base.
And so I would go out on these inspections, and I'd stop by veterinary hospitals and get to know veterinarians.
And pretty soon, you know, before I got out of the Air Force, I think I knew almost all of the practitioners in San Antonio, you know, personally.
And so I had a lot of encouragement to stay here, along with my wife, and wanted to.
And so I took the Texas boards.
And I've been here ever since.
So my interest.
Is there any difficulty in an outsider coming in and taking the Texas boards and getting your license ?
It's tough.
I was lucky.
In those days, Texas and Michigan had reciprocation.
And so all I had to do was to take the practical part of the examination.
I didn't have to take the written part of the exam and everything.
And since I had a Michigan license, it was a little easier for me at that point.
And so I went into practice with an older veterinarian who's now dead, Dr. Walter Lawrence in San Antonio.
And you asked me about how I got involved with birds.
And of course, we were.

talking about that I kinda felt that that was the time when veterinary medicine was really losing poultry practice and there was a lot of discussion in the profession editorials and how could we save this part of veterinary practice and it was primarily because veterinarians really weren't interested in poultry practice and didn't want to get involved and so I saw a couple of parakeets and people called me and I said well

you know, they brought them in, and they'd been to the pet shop, and the pet shop had given them medicine and told them all this stuff about how to treat them, and I thought to myself, you know, the same thing's going to happen with this.

Pets that people buy at pet shops, monkeys and birds and all these little animals, guinea pigs and hamsters and things like that, if veterinarians don't treat them, why, pretty soon, they're going to, you know, that part of
practice, whatever it might be, they're going to lose because we're certainly more qualified to do that than some yo-yo in a pet shop.

And even though I didn't know anything about these animals, we didn't get anything in veterinary school about them, I just tried to apply my knowledge of medicine to a species that I really didn't know a whole lot about.
And so I started doing it and pretty soon the reputation spread around and veterinarians
would get one of their clients a call and they had a sick parakeet or a sick parrot or a sick hamster or guinea pig or whatever it might be.
Well, they'd say, well, we don't treat those, but call Tom Weiss.
He treats them.
So pretty soon it began to become a part of my practice.
And, of course, in caged birds particularly, I was just down here just stumbling along trying to do the best I could.
That whole part of veterinary practice has gone through a tremendous evolution in about the last eight or nine years.
And I think it was about eight years ago, there were 40 veterinarians, myself included, that met for the first time in Kalamazoo, Michigan.
And these were guys who were interested in cage birds, treating cage birds.
And a classmate of mine in Michigan, Ron Spink,
knew that I did this, and so he contacted me, and Ron was the one who contacted veterinarians throughout the country.
And we formed an organization called the American Association of Avian Veterinarians.
And now it has over, I think, 1,200 or 1,300 members worldwide.
It's the fastest-growing specialty association in veterinary medicine.
And it has piqued a tremendous amount of interest in cave bird medicine.
It's stimulated research and sharing of information.
It was a wonderful experience for me just to get together with other veterinarians who treated these birds and share our own clinical experiences and everything.
And they now have a journal.
And we just had a meeting, the international meeting, in Houston last September.
And there were probably 500 to 600 veterinarians there from all over the world.
and papers being presented.
And of course, caged birds have become tremendously popular now as pets.
Back when I was the only one in this whole area of Texas that would even look at one and treat it, I didn't see nearly as many as I see today.
And back then, you could buy a parrot for $100 or $150.
Now they run from $300 to $8,000 for a hyacinth macaw.
I didn't see nearly as many of them as I do today.
And today I have competition.
There are many other veterinarians now who are treating birds.
Are they getting training now?
They're getting, yes.
In fact, yes.

I was about, I think, six or seven years ago, got an appointment to the faculty at A&M as an adjunct professor and went up and lectured three or four times a year on caged bird medicine to the third year class.
And now A&M is really in the forefront of this whole thing.

Mr. Richard Schubot from Florida, a very wealthy man who's really interested in these birds, and their future donated a million dollars to the veterinary school at A&M to establish a chair in caged bird medicine in the Department of Microbiology.
the school, I think, matched that.
So it's a $2 million chair, which is one of the more endowed chairs or maybe the most endowed chair in the university.
And they established the Shoebot Avian Disease Center.
And Dr. David Graham, who's an internationally recognized avian or caged bird pathologist, is now there and heading up that.
And the emphasis in teaching now is shifted away from poultry medicine to caged bird medicine.

Dr. Tizard, who's the head of the Department of Microbiology, and I had a long discussion about it, and he said, well, you know, he said there are probably eight veterinarians in the state of Texas involved in poultry medicine, and six of those eight are on the staff of the university.
And we have an obligation to support the poultry industry of the state, but we do that with diagnostic medicine and those kinds of things.
He said, we feel that our teaching emphasis should be on what the students are going to see when they get out there and practice, and that's Kate's word.
And they're in another university in the country, or veterinary school in the country, that has gone to that extent to dedicate their teaching programs to Kate's word medicine.
But to get back to my background, then I took a job.
I left and started my own practice on Broadway.
In fact, Dr. Tremere, as we talked about, and Saunders and Larson really helped me get started.
I really couldn't have done it without them.
And right around the corner from them, they leased the old Broadway Animal Hospital to me and had equipment in it and cages and everything.
In fact, Wallace moved over and started running this large animal practice out of there, too.
And we shared the old Broadway Animal Hospital.
And then I took a job.
Again, I didn't literally have a pot to pee in or a window to throw it out.
And so I took a job part time as a veterinarian, first veterinarian on the staff at Southwest Foundation for research and education for the big primate colonies.
Yeah, I think you have a friend who worked out there.
Yeah.
I was the first veterinarian that they'd ever had on their staff.
They'd just established their big baboon colony.
And I took a job there part time.
Well, it started two hours a day, gradually grew to four hours a day, and then to a full-time staff position, I kept my veterinary practice.
And at that time, that's when I hired Dr. Olin, who is now the orthopedic surgeon that had the elephant episode.
And about that time, Fred Stark, who was the director of the zoo, came to me.
and asked me if I would do the zoo work, too.
And that was a part-time position.
So that was another chance to pick up another $300, $400 a month.
And so I took that job, too.
I used to drive 150 miles a day and never got out of the city.
I would go to my office at 7 o'clock in the morning
I'd leave there at about 8 and go to Southwest Research.
I'd leave there at 11 and go to the zoo.
I'd leave the zoo at 1, go back to Southwest Research, leave there at 4.30 and go back to my practice.
So you started all this very early on in your practice.
Yes, that's right.
And so I was the zoo veterinarian for about four and a half years, and then Stubby came on and took over the zoo work at that time.
And shortly after that, then I left Southwest Research and went back to my practice full time.
So from that very beginning, I've always treated what we call exotic pets.
Those are pets other than dogs and cats.
And exotic practice was a lot different in those days.
In fact, a small percentage of it was caged birds, quite frankly.
We saw a lot of ocelots.
and surveil cats and jungle cats, margay cats, all these exotic cats that were being imported.
We saw monkeys, lots of pet monkeys.
And a lot of other indigenous wild animals.
It wasn't unusual then for people to keep raccoons and skunks as pets and everything.
So we saw a lot of wild animals as pets.
And then I used to almost hate to see the spring come because
when all the baby birds started coming out of the nests and stuff, and people would find this little bird in their yard, and they'd call their veterinarian and say, oh, we don't treat birds.
Call Tom Weiss.
And boy, my phone would just ring off the wall.
I mean, they would just get deluged with it.
Now, most of those imported wild animals that people would try to keep as pets are now on an endangered species list.
And so we seldom see pet monkeys anymore.
We don't see any of the exotic cats except the big cats that breed well in captivity, cougars and jaguars and lions and tigers.
And there are guys breeding those and selling them to people as pets and that type of thing.
So now almost I would say that 80% to 85% of my exotic pet practice are caged birds.
And we see, and I see in my practice, 20 to 30 birds a day.
Is that right?
We do, in fact, we have a bacteriology set up in the hospital, and we average about 80 to 100 cultures a month.
And virtually all those, or 90% of those, are in birds.
Are there some recent really strong importation restraints?
Yes, and that's happening now in birds.
Many, in fact, almost all the macaws except the blue and gold now are on threatened or endangered species lists.
And many of the other species, and we're going to see the very same thing happen, that the importation of these larger cytosine birds is just going to dry up.
And so we're going to have to depend on domestic production.
With the advent of surgical sexing, you know, most of these birds are not sexually dimorphic.
You can't tell the male from the female.
And with the advent of a laparoscope about eight or nine years ago, why, veterinarians went in and started surgically sexing these birds.
And up until that time, the success of domestic breeding was just very, very poor, scanty at best.
Aviculturists were lucky when they happened to get
a pair that would breed in captivity or get them paired up right.
Now, why the success is tremendous.
We're seeing more and more domestic...
Yes, yes.
More and more...
I have one client who probably raises 200 domestically born larger citizen birds a year.
And so hopefully there are enough of these birds breeding in captivity that we're going to be able to maybe meet the demand
with domestic production.
So far, we can't.
And we're a ways away from doing that.
Do you have any ostrich on here?
No.
In fact, I get ostrich calls just like Stubby was talking about, why I refer them to him.
Mainly because I can't really be out of my office.
I'm just too busy to go out.
That's a large animal practice, isn't it?
It really is.
And I can't go out on a call to do these.
I've had numbers of young ones brought into the hospital.
And we've done some orthopedic procedures.
some other things from time to time.
But, of course, they've become very popular now.
They're in vogue.
And so Stubby's going to make his fame and fortune on his ostrich practice.
Okay, nobody knows anything about it.
How about the llamas?
Well, they're in the same boat right now.
That's right.
Well, you know, there's very little.
The problem you get into, the challenges you get into in exotic pet practice are relative to the fact that there's very little basic research
done on these animals.
There's just not any money out there to fund research.
And so you really have to apply your knowledge and a little bit of your knowledge in maybe anatomy and physiology of a life-type species.
And then a little bit of, for instance, right now in birds, almost all of our antibiotic dosages
are extrapolated from dogs, cats, and people.
No, we're using antibiotics.
They don't use the chickens.
And in fact, the birds' predominant bacterial problems in birds are gram-negative infections.
And they're, I think, basically a product of these birds being in captivity and being exposed to human and carnivore type of environments.
These are coliform organisms that are normal in our gastrointestinal tract.
They've sampled
wild populations of birds and they seldom ever find a gram-negative bug in their gastrointestinal tract.
And yet we deal with the predominant problem with this in these birds in captivity.
And so we're using antibiotics like amikacin and gentamicin and piperacillin and tricarcillin and the third generation cephalosporins because these are bacteria that are very antibiotic resistant.
And so all of our dosages have been extrapolated down from human dosages on a weight basis.
And there's a lot of controversy now because of the rapid metabolism of the bird, how frequently they should be given to maintain adequate blood levels.
And we hope there's a guy in North Carolina, Dr. Kevin Flammer,

now that has some funding, and he's doing some blood level studies in different antibiotics in these birds, in different species, and hopefully we're going to have some very meaningful information on what we should be giving them.
Most of it is trial and error and experience, and we seem to get results at certain levels and things.
So this is the kind of thing that we face.
And the same thing with Stubby, when he goes out here to treat an ostrich or a llama or
or a nigyle antelope or whatever.
He has to rely on knowledge, on clinical knowledge that has been shared among zoo veterinarians and everything and is gleaned out of maybe worldwide literature.
But there's so many big gaps in this that a lot of stuff is empirical.
It's been based upon clinical trials.
Some guy treated a case and wrote it up and published it in a zoo journal or something of that nature.
It's not been controlled, definitive experiments.
Same way in nutrition.

And a lot of our problems in exotic species, birds included, but all these others, are nutritional problems and management problems because we really lack the knowledge to know, again, and the big four-stomach puss talk, why we're basically extrapolating our knowledge of cattle and sheep and domestics to these species and
And we may be way, way off base in a lot of areas.
Are there many people now going into a defined exotic bird or animal practice?
Well, birds there are.
There's a tremendous interest in that.
There always is.
The student chapters at A&M, for instance, they have a student chapter of the American Association of Zoo Veterinarians.
And they always have a big membership.
Kids are interested.
They all dream about getting a job in a zoo.
The problem is there are not many jobs out there in zoos.
And so I have, you know, we do preceptorships in my practice and have for quite some time.
And so I get students from all over the country.
